// Issue #13 — labeled queries fixture for `benches/quant_sweep.rs`.
//
// Format: one JSON object per line. Comment lines (starting with `#` or
// `//`) and blank lines are skipped by the bench loader. Schema matches
// `memex_lib::eval_ndcg::LabeledQuery`:
//
//   { "query": "<free-text the user would type>",
//     "relevant_ids": ["<session-id 1>", "<session-id 2>", ...] }
//
// `relevant_ids` are listed in descending relevance order (most relevant
// first). nDCG@10 will count each ID found in the top-10 results,
// discounted by rank.
//
// ## How to populate this file
//
// 1. Pick ~20 queries that span the kinds of recall you care about:
//    error-mode lookups, code-snippet recall, project-spanning topic
//    search, identifier search, etc.
//
// 2. For each query, manually identify 3-5 sessions in your corpus that
//    a perfect retrieval system would return. Use `memex` itself or
//    `~/.claude/projects/**/*.jsonl` directly — the session_id is the
//    file basename (UUID).
//
// 3. Commit this file. The benchmark loads it deterministically; identical
//    fixture + identical QuantMode → identical nDCG.
//
// The 3 examples below are placeholders demonstrating the format. They
// reference made-up session IDs and will produce a zero nDCG on any real
// corpus — replace them with your own.

{"query": "vector search recall benchmark", "relevant_ids": ["00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001", "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002"]}
{"query": "qdrant payload index migration", "relevant_ids": ["00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000003"]}
{"query": "memex landing page rebuild", "relevant_ids": ["00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000004", "00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000005"]}
